SIMPLE: mail
RECORDS: 6

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mail
<hw>Mail</hw> <pr>(m⟦amac⟧l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A spot.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mail</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mail
<hw>Mail</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>maille</ets>, OF. also
<ets>maaille</ets>, LL. <ets>medalia</ets>. See <er>Medal</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A small piece of money; especially, an English silver
half-penny of the time of <person>Henry V.</person></def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <altsp>[Written also <asp>maile</asp>, and
<asp>maille</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Rent; tribute.</def> <mark>[Obs., except in certain
compounds and phrases, as blackmail, mails and duties, etc.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mail and duties</b></col> <fld>(Scots Law)</fld>, <cd>the
rents of an estate, in whatever form paid.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mail</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Mail
<hw>Mail</hw> <pr>(m⟦amac⟧l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>maile</ets>, <ets>maille</ets>, F. <ets>maille</ets> a ring of
mail, mesh, network, a coat of mail, fr. L. <ets>macula</ets> spot, a
mesh of a net. Cf. <er>Macle</er>, <er>Macula</er>,
<er>Mascle</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A flexible fabric made of metal
rings interlinked. It was used especially for defensive armor.</def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Chain mail</b></col>, <col><b>Coat of
mail</b></col></mcol>. <cd>See under <er>Chain</er>, and
<er>Coat</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence generally, armor, or any defensive
covering.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A contrivance of interlinked
rings, for rubbing off the loose hemp on lines and white
cordage.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any hard protective covering of
an animal, as the scales and plates of reptiles, shell of a lobster,
etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We . . . strip the lobster of his scarlet <qex>mail</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Gay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mail</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Mail
<hw>Mail</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To arm with
mail.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To pinion.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mail</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Mail
<hw>Mail</hw> <pr>(m⟦amac⟧l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>male</ets> bag, OF. <ets>male</ets>, F. <ets>malle</ets> bag,
trunk, mail, OHG. <ets>malaha</ets>, <ets>malha</ets>, wallet; akin to
D. <ets>maal</ets>, <ets>male</ets>; cf. Gael. & Ir. <ets>mala</ets>,
Gr. <grk>molgo`s</grk> hide, skin.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A bag; a
wallet.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The bag or bags with the letters, papers, or other
matter contained therein, conveyed under public authority from one post
office to another; the whole system of appliances used by government in
the conveyance and delivery of mail matter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is a <qex>mail</qex> come in to-day, with letters dated
Hague.</q> <rj><qau>Tatler.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which comes in the mail; letters, etc.,
received through the post office.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A trunk, box, or bag, in which clothing, etc., may
be carried.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir W.
Scott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mail catcher</b></col>, <cd>an iron rod, or other
contrivance, attached to a railroad car for catching a mail bag while
the train is in motion.</cd> -- <col><b>Mail guard</b></col>, <cd>an
officer whose duty it is to guard the public mails.</cd>
<mark>[Eng.]</mark> -- <col><b>Mail train</b></col>, <cd>a railroad
train carrying the mail.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mail</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Mail
<hw>Mail</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Mailed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Mailing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To deliver into the custody of
the postoffice officials, or place in a government letter box, for
transmission by mail; to post; <as>as, to <ex>mail</ex> a
letter</as>.</def> <mark>[U. S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In the United States <xex>to mail</xex> and <xex>to
post</xex> are both in common use; as, to <xex>mail</xex> or
<xex>post</xex> a letter. In England <xex>post</xex> is the commoner
usage.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mailable</ent>⟦br⟧
